{
  "texts": [
    "Technically, DPO or its variants, such as those of SimPO (Azar et al., 2024) and (Zhao et al., 2023), are essentially based on BT preference assumption (Bradley and Terry, 1952) which maximizes the relative reward differences between chosen and rejected responses (Tajwar et al., 2024).",
    "However, the likelihood of the chosen response can continue to decrease during training as long as the relative difference in the likelihoods between the chosen and rejected responses remains large.",
    "In this paper, we address this limitation by proposing a novel objective based on mutual information maximization.",
    "4.1 Mutual Information Maximization for Large Language Alignment In this section, we connect DPO to mutual information maximization.",
    "We demonstrate that RLHF is a special case of the mutual information maximization problem by defining a specialized score function (or critic) approximated by a neural network."
  ]
}